Books


    Helmet for my Pillow - the hard life of a Marine
  

    Interesting perspective of a combat Marine. I was a platoon commander in Vietnam. Interestingly, while the equipment has changed, and while the training and physical shape is better, the issues are the same. Seemingly the author doesn't understand what is at stake.He apparently went into the Marines to prove something to or about himself. He ended up in a shooting war. That's what Marines do. One needs to grasp that from the beginning. The psychological strain of combat is significant, but to this day it seems poorly understood. Fick is only one in a long line of men who have had this issue. The fact combat runs faster today only makes the strain quicker to attach itself to a person.Today PTSD is the preferred term for what Fick went through. But it really isn't PTSD. It's moral injury. Most of us have an internal compass that tells us right from wrong. (Those biblically inclined will note Genesis 2). When up against killing another human being, we tend to balk. Fink balked. Lt. Col Grossman wrote a number of books about this subject, but mostly they are observations of fact, not really an understanding of what happens.Fink was not decompressed properly. Neither were any of us from Vietnam. The last proper decompression was WWII when the troops had time to just talk amongst themselves and then be greeted by a grateful nation on returning.I hope he has managed to find his peace somewhere.
  

Devereaux
July 20, 2017


Overall: 5







